{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019PcHAzWgdcXgRLoArmiFKD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the setup:\n- Prometheus container runs on port 9090\n- Prometheus service exposes port 8000 -> targetPort 9090\n- The Prometheus config only scrapes `localhost:9090` (itself), but no RabbitMQ\n\nThe fix is:\n1. Update the `prometheus-config` ConfigMap to add a scrape job for the 3 RabbitMQ pods\n2. Use the headless service DNS to reach each pod individually:\n   - `rabbitmq-0.rabbitmq-headless.{namespace}.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n   - `rabbitmq-1.rabbitmq-headless.{namespace}.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n   - `rabbitmq-2.rabbitmq-headless.{namespace}.svc.cluster.local:15692`\n3. After updating the ConfigMap, I can reload Prometheus via the lifecycle API (`POST /-/reload`) since `--web.enable-lifecycle` is enabled, or restart the pod\n\nI'll update the ConfigMap with a new scrape job targeting the RabbitMQ pods on port 15692 at the `/metrics` endpoint.\n\nThe namespace is quite long: `karma-rabbitmq-maximal-lifecycle-roll-e44cf02f-cluster-a`. I'll use the headless service to scrape each pod individually rather than going through the load-balanced endpoint, so I get three distinct targets.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":614,"cache_read_input_tokens":33366,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":614},"output_tokens":38,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7ce06994-a8d0-4fc8-b035-fa752d1456e6","uuid":"4ee6d65a-d7bf-4394-ae6f-09a0e6e2e379","request_id":"req_011CcLtwuKwigXA2ctfwhVJ6"}
