{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01NeTncMyW5xondwZUmDGLx9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Done. Here's a summary of what was changed and why:\n\n**Root cause:** The `prometheus-config` ConfigMap only had a self-scrape job (`localhost:9090`) — no RabbitMQ job at all.\n\n**Fix — one ConfigMap update, two additions:**\n\n1. **Added a `rabbitmq` scrape job** targeting each pod individually via the headless service DNS (`rabbitmq-{0,1,2}.rabbitmq-headless.<ns>.svc.cluster.local:15692`). Using the headless service ensures Prometheus talks to each pod separately and shows 3 distinct targets rather than a load-balanced single target through the ClusterIP service.\n\n2. **Added a recording rule `rabbitmq_up = up{job=\"rabbitmq\"}`** in a `rabbitmq_rules.yml` key. RabbitMQ's built-in Prometheus plugin (port 15692) doesn't expose `rabbitmq_up` — that's only from the community `rabbitmq_exporter`. Prometheus auto-generates an `up` metric per target (1 = reachable, 0 = unreachable); the recording rule aliases it to the expected name. No external exporter, CRD, or operator needed.\n\nResults:\n- 3 RabbitMQ targets `health: \"up\"` in Prometheus\n- `rabbitmq_up` returns 3 samples, all value `\"1\"`\n- All 3 RabbitMQ pods still `1/1 Running`, no restarts"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":215,"cache_read_input_tokens":43977,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":215},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"7ce06994-a8d0-4fc8-b035-fa752d1456e6","uuid":"e3ffe2e9-f59e-42d5-9841-e0e7351b0297","request_id":"req_011CcLuApAFXY21NcJgzdpEj"}
